From: Gabi Falk <gabifalk@gmx.com>
Date: Sun, 8 Jun 2026 08:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] nptl: forward the seventh argument from __syscall_cancel()

On configurations that define HAVE_CANCELABLE_SYSCALL_WITH_7_ARGS
(currently only mips o32) a cancellable syscall may take seven
arguments.  __internal_syscall_cancel() correctly forwards the seventh
argument to the architecture entry point using __SYSCALL_CANCEL7_ARG7
(which expands to "a7,"), but __syscall_cancel() forwards it to
__internal_syscall_cancel() using __SYSCALL_CANCEL7_ARG instead, which
expands to the literal filler "0," used by the zero-to-six argument
dispatch macros.

As a result the seventh argument is replaced with 0 for every seven
argument cancellable syscall issued through the public wrappers.  On
mips o32 this affects sync_file_range(), whose "flags" argument is
silently zeroed.

Use __SYSCALL_CANCEL7_ARG7 so the real seventh argument is forwarded.

Signed-off-by: Gabi Falk <gabifalk@gmx.com>
---
diff --git a/nptl/cancellation.c b/nptl/cancellation.c
index 0e9c8c7..1a2b3c4 100644
--- a/nptl/cancellation.c
+++ b/nptl/cancellation.c
@@ -73,7 +73,7 @@ __syscall_cancel (__syscall_arg_t a1, __syscall_arg_t a2,
 		  __SYSCALL_CANCEL7_ARG_DEF __syscall_arg_t nr)
 {
   long int r = __internal_syscall_cancel (a1, a2, a3, a4, a5, a6,
-					  __SYSCALL_CANCEL7_ARG nr);
+					  __SYSCALL_CANCEL7_ARG7 nr);
   return __glibc_unlikely (INTERNAL_SYSCALL_ERROR_P (r))
 	 ? SYSCALL_ERROR_LABEL (INTERNAL_SYSCALL_ERRNO (r))
 	 : r;
